For us incarnate

864
01:01:03,500 --> 01:01:05,606
O Word of God

865
01:01:05,677 --> 01:01:08,775
For us incarnate

866
01:01:08,845 --> 01:01:13,155
By faith we hear Thine angels sing

867
01:01:18,285 --> 01:01:22,082
- Their hymns
- Angels sing their hymns

868
01:01:22,157 --> 01:01:25,890
Of praise to Thee their King

869
01:01:25,613 --> 01:01:30,348
We join with them in adoration

870
01:01:35,788 --> 01:01:40,130
We pour
We pour to Thee

871
01:01:39,628 --> 01:01:43,273
Our supplication

872
01:01:43,341 --> 01:01:45,829
That Thou wouldst

873
01:01:45,901 --> 01:01:49,097
Grant us Lord

874
01:01:49,165 --> 01:01:54,828
Salvation

875
01:02:02,893 --> 01:02:05,413
Boys, that was beautiful.

876
01:02:05,485 --> 01:02:07,340
Really beautiful.

877
01:02:07,789 --> 01:02:12,229
You've all grown up so since
the bishop and I lived in this parish.

878
01:02:12,301 --> 01:02:15,051
I hardly recognized any of you.

879
01:02:15,117 --> 01:02:17,004
I'm so proud of you.

880
01:02:17,068 --> 01:02:19,272
I know he will be to.

881
01:02:19,340 --> 01:02:21,195
Thank you.

882
01:02:21,260 --> 01:02:23,790
Mr. Miller, that was wonderful.

883
01:02:24,470 --> 01:02:26,346
I can't thank you enough.

884
01:02:26,413 --> 01:02:30,210
- And you, Mr. Dudley.
- I'm sorry the bishop isn't here.

885
01:02:33,901 --> 01:02:35,973
- Are you all right?
- Yes. Thank you.

886
01:02:36,749 --> 01:02:39,051
What is keeping Stevens?

887
01:02:39,117 --> 01:02:40,972
Stevens, there you are.

888
01:02:41,037 --> 01:02:44,866
I'm sorry but the furniture shop
is closed until after New Year's.

889
01:02:44,941 --> 01:02:48,138
I can't find a plumber.
We're out of turpentine.

890
01:02:48,205 --> 01:02:50,954
- This is preposterous.
- What about some witch hazel?

891
01:02:52,844 --> 01:02:55,692
- May I use your telephone?
- Of course. It's over there.

892
01:02:55,757 --> 01:02:57,131
Thank you.

893
01:03:10,349 --> 01:03:12,356
Tilda, this is Bishop Brougham.

894
01:03:12,429 --> 01:03:15,658
Will you bring a pair of my trousers
over to Mrs. Hamilton's house?

895
01:03:18,445 --> 01:03:21,674
What difference does it make?
Just bring me another pair of trousers.

896
01:03:21,740 --> 01:03:23,912
Thank you.

897
01:03:23,981 --> 01:03:27,177
I'm so sorry this has happened.

898
01:03:27,245 --> 01:03:29,700
If only I could contact Julia or Dudley.

899
01:03:29,773 --> 01:03:31,781
Don't be nervous, Bishop.

900
01:03:33,453 --> 01:03:35,209
Have a chair.

901
01:03:35,277 --> 01:03:37,132
Thank you, I have one.

902
01:03:44,653 --> 01:03:45,830
He isn't here.

903
01:03:45,900 --> 01:03:48,999
Perhaps the meeting was
more important than he thought.

904
01:03:49,069 --> 01:03:50,924
I suppose.

905
01:03:51,756 --> 01:03:53,611
We'd better go home.

906
01:03:56,812 --> 01:03:58,700
Dudley, it's strange thing.

907
01:03:58,765 --> 01:04:00,620
What's strange?

908
01:04:00,685 --> 01:04:04,482
You make me feel as if everything
is going to be all right.

909
01:04:05,070 --> 01:04:06,793
- It could be if...
- If what?

910
01:04:08,301 --> 01:04:11,050
If people could only learn
to behave like human beings.

911
01:04:14,285 --> 01:04:15,812
Hey, taxi.

912
01:04:22,732 --> 01:04:24,042
Here's a cab.

913
01:04:26,285 --> 01:04:28,139
Will you please wait, Sylvester?

914
01:04:28,205 --> 01:04:30,060
Sure, mister.

915
01:04:30,125 --> 01:04:32,040
Sylvester?

916
01:04:39,400 --> 01:04:41,356
Good evening. I'll be right with you.

917
01:04:41,420 --> 01:04:45,340
This is one of
our most exclusive models.

918
01:04:44,653 --> 01:04:46,955
It's lovely.
Simply ravishing!

919
01:04:47,021 --> 01:04:48,744
So chic, so young.

920
01:04:48,813 --> 01:04:51,682
- It is sweet, isn't it?
- It's stunning.

921
01:04:51,757 --> 01:04:55,820
Not everyone could wear such a daring
hat. It was made for madame.

922
01:05:11,948 --> 01:05:15,843
How did you know
my name was Sylvester?

923
01:05:15,917 --> 01:05:19,180
It's up there on your card.

924
01:05:21,900 --> 01:05:23,940
Could you drive us
through the park, please?

925
01:05:24,013 --> 01:05:26,230
That's out of your way.

926
01:05:25,644 --> 01:05:28,230
Sylvester,
are you getting bored with us?

927
01:05:28,301 --> 01:05:31,814
Oh, no. I'll drive you
to Mexico City, if you want.

928
01:05:31,885 --> 01:05:33,259
Thank you.

929
01:05:35,500 --> 01:05:37,355
I'm having so much fun.

930
01:05:38,220 --> 01:05:39,431
- Are you?
- Yes.

931
01:05:39,600 --> 01:05:42,916
- Are you really?
- I feel as if I'm doing something bad.

932
01:05:42,989 --> 01:05:44,777
- Why?
- I don't know.

933
01:05:45,837 --> 01:05:48,390
I seems wrong to have
so much fun but...

934
01:05:48,461 --> 01:05:51,308
I can't figure out why.

935
01:05:51,373 --> 01:05:54,689
You folks know
what's wrong with this country?

936
01:05:54,765 --> 01:05:57,448
I've heard several versions
of that.

937
01:05:57,660 --> 01:06:00,266
- Do you know?
- I think I do.

938
01:06:01,164 --> 01:06:03,717
Too many people who don't know
where they're going...

939
01:06:03,788 --> 01:06:06,276
and they want to get there too fast.

940
01:06:06,349 --> 01:06:10,280
Take you two.
I'd call you unusual.

941
01:06:09,644 --> 01:06:12,361
Thank you. You're very perceptive.

942
01:06:12,428 --> 01:06:16,323
You know your destination
but are in no hurry to get there.

943
01:06:16,397 --> 01:06:19,212
You want to enjoy
some scenery en route.

944
01:06:19,277 --> 01:06:21,630
And you're not reluctant to spend
an extra four bits...

945
01:06:22,310 --> 01:06:23,686
for a detour with Mother Nature.

946
01:06:24,716 --> 01:06:26,026
Look where you're going!

947
01:06:28,748 --> 01:06:31,083
Well, my goodness.

948
01:06:31,149 --> 01:06:33,866
Did you see the way
I missed that truck?

949
01:06:33,933 --> 01:06:37,446
- It was like a miracle.
- Yes, but don't overplay your hand.

950
01:06:49,990 --> 01:06:51,436
Sylvester, pull up here.

951
01:06:51,600 --> 01:06:52,745
We're going skating.

952
01:06:52,813 --> 01:06:55,268
We mustn't. It's late.
We couldn't.

953
01:06:55,341 --> 01:06:58,210
- Do you think we could?
- Henry can wait a little longer.

954
01:06:58,285 --> 01:07:00,456
- Yeah.
- Sylvester, stop the car.

955
01:07:06,829 --> 01:07:08,684
- I am wicked.
- If you are, so am I.

956
01:07:08,749 --> 01:07:11,051
And that's impossible.
Can you skate?

957
01:07:11,117 --> 01:07:13,605
I used to but I'm too old now.

958
01:07:13,676 --> 01:07:16,459
Put on some skates.
You'll find out how young you are.

959
01:07:36,812 --> 01:07:38,787
I don't know about this.

960
01:07:57,293 --> 01:07:59,147
Relax. That's right.

961
01:08:11,341 --> 01:08:13,195
Pretty hat.

962
01:08:44,077 --> 01:08:46,466
- Why, Dudley!
- Now you.

963
01:08:46,900 --> 01:08:49,300
- Oh, no. L...
- Come on.

964
01:08:56,780 --> 01:08:59,977
- Dudley, this is heaven.
- You found the perfect word.

965
01:09:22,477 --> 01:09:24,484
Look what I'm doing!

966
01:09:25,900 --> 01:09:28,999
You're a beautiful skater.
In fact, you're beautiful.

967
01:09:37,197 --> 01:09:39,401
Look at Sylvester!

968
01:09:44,150 --> 01:09:45,420
Now, Sylvester.

969
01:10:08,684 --> 01:10:10,277
- Excuse me.
- Sure.

970
01:10:10,348 --> 01:10:12,690
Keep cool, Sylvester!

971
01:10:14,637 --> 01:10:16,492
Relax.

972
01:10:18,604 --> 01:10:20,960
That's right. Come on.

973
01:10:20,620 --> 01:10:22,922
Give me the other one.
That's it.

974
01:10:22,988 --> 01:10:25,476
Relax. No, not collapse.

975
01:10:29,260 --> 01:10:31,115
Hang on to me.

976
01:10:37,980 --> 01:10:39,817
Don't leave me!

977
01:10:54,380 --> 01:10:56,235
How am I doing, Dudley?

978
01:11:08,972 --> 01:11:10,827
Wait for me!

979
01:11:57,613 --> 01:11:59,468
Thank you, Dudley.

980
01:11:59,830 --> 01:12:02,631
- How much do I owe you?
- Not a cent, my friend.

981
01:12:02,700 --> 01:12:06,377
My pockets are bulging with the coins
of self-satisfaction.

982
01:12:06,445 --> 01:12:08,670
- Know why?
- I'd love to know.

983
01:12:09,380 --> 01:12:12,614
Because you two have restored
my faith in human nature.

984
01:12:12,684 --> 01:12:14,724
Good night, Dudley and Julia.

985
01:12:14,796 --> 01:12:16,771
- Good night, Sylvester.
- Good night, Sylvester.

986
01:12:22,796 --> 01:12:24,684
Sylvester is a noble soul.

987
01:12:24,748 --> 01:12:28,904
His children and his children's children
will rise up and call him blessed.

988
01:12:30,284 --> 01:12:33,099
This has been the most wonderful
evening I've had in years.

989
01:12:33,164 --> 01:12:35,815
This has been the most wonderful
evening I've had in centuries.

990
01:12:37,228 --> 01:12:41,352
- I hope I haven't left the key...
- Go on in. It's open.

991
01:12:41,420 --> 01:12:41,484
Thank you.

992
01:12:41,484 --> 01:12:43,306
Thank you.

993
01:12:43,372 --> 01:12:45,761
- Hello, Queenie.
- Hello, Queenie. How are you?

994
01:12:45,836 --> 01:12:47,494
- Can I help you?
- Yes, please.

995
01:12:48,140 --> 01:12:49,931
- All right.
- Oh! You got my shoe.

996
01:12:49,996 --> 01:12:52,484
- Hello, Henry.
- Well, Henry.

997
01:12:53,060 --> 01:12:55,207
I thought you were going to meet us
at St. Timothy's.

998
01:12:55,276 --> 01:12:56,738
What happened to you?

999
01:12:56,812 --> 01:12:59,049
- Can I take that?
- Thank you. You'll never guess.

1000
01:13:00,013 --> 01:13:01,867
- We went skating.
- The coat...

1001
01:13:01,933 --> 01:13:03,394
There you are.

1002
01:13:04,108 --> 01:13:05,668
- See you in a minute.
- All right.

1003
01:13:07,724 --> 01:13:10,375
- Skating?
- Yes. Dudley's a marvelous skater.

1004
01:13:10,444 --> 01:13:12,778
He made me imagine that I was good.

1005
01:13:12,845 --> 01:13:17,100
You should have heard the boys
at St. Timothy's. It was heavenly.

1006
01:13:17,164 --> 01:13:19,652
- I'm sure of that.
- Did you have a successful meeting?

1007
01:13:19,724 --> 01:13:22,290
- Did you?
- Satisfactory.

1008
01:13:21,644 --> 01:13:25,280
Good. I want to see Debby
before she goes to sleep.

1009
01:13:26,828 --> 01:13:29,098
- You haven't said a word about it.
- About what?

1010
01:13:29,165 --> 01:13:31,270
My new hat.

1011
01:13:34,732 --> 01:13:36,968
- What do you think?
- Charming.

1012
01:13:37,996 --> 01:13:39,851
Thank you.
I'll be right down.

1013
01:13:41,900 --> 01:13:44,747
I know that Julia is
absolutely blameless in this.

1014
01:13:44,812 --> 01:13:47,682
- Of course she is.
- You stopped me from joining you.

1015
01:13:47,756 --> 01:13:50,277
Julia had a very good time.

1016
01:13:50,348 --> 01:13:52,006
I didn't.

1017
01:13:53,292 --> 01:13:56,074
If you'd sent me to Mrs. Hamilton's
I would have gone.

1018
01:13:56,141 --> 01:13:58,726
You didn't.
So I went with your wife.

1019
01:13:58,796 --> 01:14:00,901
Is that part of
the normal duties of an...

1020
01:14:06,092 --> 01:14:08,040
Of an angel?

1021
01:14:07,628 --> 01:14:11,654
Sometimes angels must rush in
where fools fear to tread.

1022
01:14:11,724 --> 01:14:14,659
I don't know what that means
and don't explain it.

1023
01:14:17,900 --> 01:14:19,722
You can go now.

1024
01:14:19,788 --> 01:14:21,763
- I've solved my problem.
- Have you?

1025
01:14:21,836 --> 01:14:25,030
Mrs. Hamilton is giving the money
for the cathedral.

1026
01:14:24,620 --> 01:14:26,824
That was a foregone conclusion...

1027
01:14:26,892 --> 01:14:30,187
if you were willing to sacrifice
your principles.

1028
01:14:32,140 --> 01:14:35,402
Don't you think this glorious edifice
is worth it?

1029
01:14:37,292 --> 01:14:40,110
I'm not so sure of its glory.

1030
01:14:39,628 --> 01:14:42,181
- You're not?
- No, I'm not.

1031
01:14:43,340 --> 01:14:45,729
These are lean years for the world.

1032
01:14:45,804 --> 01:14:49,317
So many people need food and shelter.

1033
01:14:49,388 --> 01:14:53,000
That big roof could make
so many little roofs.

1034
01:14:53,068 --> 01:14:57,225
We're dealing with a materialistic
woman who doesn't care about that.

1035
01:14:57,292 --> 01:14:59,147
Did you try?

1036
01:15:00,236 --> 01:15:02,822
It's all arranged.
It's finished.

1037
01:15:02,893 --> 01:15:05,892
You came so that I could have
a cathedral. Now I want you to go.

1038
01:15:05,964 --> 01:15:09,000
Get out of my life and away from Julia.

1039
01:15:09,260 --> 01:15:12,642
Pray for that. It was
your prayer that brought me here.

1040
01:15:34,988 --> 01:15:38,021
- That was no prayer.
- It was right from my heart.

1041
01:15:38,092 --> 01:15:40,640
- I want you to go.
- Julia doesn't.

1042
01:15:42,412 --> 01:15:44,103
Get out!

1043
01:15:46,028 --> 01:15:49,476
Julia's coming back.
Don't let her see you like that.

1044
01:15:49,980 --> 01:15:51,403
Try to calm yourself.

1045
01:16:05,196 --> 01:16:07,050
Debby wants to say good night to Dudley.

1046
01:16:08,140 --> 01:16:09,449
- Where is he?
- He's gone.

1047
01:16:09,660 --> 01:16:11,142
- Where?
- How should I know?

1048
01:16:12,684 --> 01:16:14,823
- Why did he leave?
- I got rid of him.

1049
01:16:14,892 --> 01:16:17,675
- I fired him.
- Why?

1050
01:16:17,740 --> 01:16:20,806
He's incompetent
and I can't stand the sight of him!

1051
01:16:48,876 --> 01:16:52,454
Mummy, I'm sure that Dudley's
never coming back.

1052
01:16:53,388 --> 01:16:55,843
Darling, you must never say never.

1053
01:16:55,916 --> 01:16:57,771
Where is he?

1054
01:16:58,412 --> 01:17:00,267
Come here, dear.

1055
01:17:02,924 --> 01:17:05,063
Listen to me.

1056
01:17:05,132 --> 01:17:07,815
Dudley wouldn't leave
without saying a word.

1057
01:17:07,884 --> 01:17:11,233
Beside, he promised to tell you
about Santa Claus.

1058
01:17:11,308 --> 01:17:13,163
He knows him very well.

1059
01:17:14,700 --> 01:17:16,740
But it's almost Christmas Eve.

1060
01:17:17,836 --> 01:17:19,746
Soon I'll have to go to bed.

1061
01:17:19,819 --> 01:17:22,800
I told you he wouldn't leave
without saying a word.

1062
01:17:23,220 --> 01:17:24,677
- Would he, Matilda?
- Oh, no.

1063
01:17:24,748 --> 01:17:27,683
That wouldn't be like Mr. Dudley.

1064
01:17:27,755 --> 01:17:30,658
Come along, Debby.
I'll get you ready for dinner.

1065
01:17:30,732 --> 01:17:34,344
- Will you come see me later?
- Of course.

1066
01:17:56,396 --> 01:17:58,251
Here is the list of your calls.

1067
01:17:58,316 --> 01:18:00,683
- Ending at Mrs. Hamilton's.
- Thank you.

1068
01:18:00,747 --> 01:18:03,617
Miss Cassaway, here is the manuscript
to my Christmas sermon.

1069
01:18:03,692 --> 01:18:07,848
I shall want the original
and five carbons for the press.

1070
01:18:07,916 --> 01:18:11,113
If you finish before I come back,
leave them on my desk.

1071
01:18:13,804 --> 01:18:17,360
I'm sorry to keep you so long
on Christmas Eve.

1072
01:18:16,652 --> 01:18:20,040
I understand.
It must be done.

1073
01:18:21,964 --> 01:18:23,819
I'm ready to start out now.

1074
01:18:24,844 --> 01:18:27,266
We're going to the Trubb-Shaws,
then...

1075
01:18:29,644 --> 01:18:31,651
Then to the Van Dovers.

1076
01:18:31,724 --> 01:18:34,280
Good-bye, Miss Cassaway.

1077
01:18:44,459 --> 01:18:46,794
- Sylvester!
- Hello, Julia.

1078
01:18:46,860 --> 01:18:48,202
What are you doing here?

1079
01:18:48,268 --> 01:18:52,130
I've been waiting about an hour
hoping for another skating party.

1080
01:18:52,204 --> 01:18:54,276
I didn't want to miss it.
Where's Dudley?

1081
01:18:54,348 --> 01:18:56,203
You got a preacher with you.

1082
01:18:57,387 --> 01:18:59,329
Oh, I know!

1083
01:18:59,404 --> 01:19:01,793
You and Dudley are getting married!

1084
01:19:02,604 --> 01:19:05,865
Sylvester, this is my husband,
Bishop Brougham.

1085
01:19:05,932 --> 01:19:08,233
- How do you do?
- Oh.

1086
01:19:09,676 --> 01:19:11,618
247 North Maple.

1087
01:19:16,876 --> 01:19:19,015
247 North Maple.

1088
01:19:34,219 --> 01:19:35,626
- Mildred.
- Oh!

1089
01:19:38,284 --> 01:19:40,804
Dudley, it's you.
I didn't see...

1090
01:19:40,876 --> 01:19:43,691
Where have you been?
We've been worrying about you.

1091
01:19:43,756 --> 01:19:46,309
And poor Mrs. Brougham.

1092
01:19:46,380 --> 01:19:49,380
- What about her?
- She's been in and out of here all day.

1093
01:19:49,452 --> 01:19:52,201
Asking if we've seen or heard from you.

1094
01:19:52,268 --> 01:19:55,333
- Where is she?
- She and the bishop are making calls...

1095
01:19:55,404 --> 01:19:57,258
finishing at Mrs. Hamilton's.

1096
01:20:01,060 --> 01:20:02,890
- I'll type this for you.
- Oh, no.

1097
01:20:02,956 --> 01:20:04,330
- You go.
- The bishop told me...

1098
01:20:04,396 --> 01:20:07,210
It's almost Christmas Eve.
You must have shopping to do.

1099
01:20:08,939 --> 01:20:11,274
- Go on.
- Thank you, Dudley.

1100
01:20:13,835 --> 01:20:15,723
Merry Christmas, Mildred.

1101
01:20:15,788 --> 01:20:17,643
Merry Christmas, Dudley.

1102
01:20:48,108 --> 01:20:49,962
Take a sermon.

1103
01:20:51,340 --> 01:20:54,373
Tonight, I want to tell you the story
of an empty stocking.

1104
01:20:56,396 --> 01:20:59,265
Once upon a midnight clear,
there was a chilïs cry.

1105
01:21:00,427 --> 01:21:02,729
A blazing star hung over a stable...

1106
01:21:02,795 --> 01:21:04,999
and wise men came with birthday gifts.

1107
01:21:05,067 --> 01:21:06,474
Have you got that?

1108
01:21:06,890 --> 01:21:10,020
Good. We haven't forgotten that night
down the centuries.

1109
01:21:10,092 --> 01:21:13,408
We celebrate it with stars hung
on the Christmas tree and bells...

1110
01:21:13,484 --> 01:21:15,972
and gifts, especially gifts.

1111
01:21:16,044 --> 01:21:20,353
We buy them, wrap them
and put them under the tree.

1112
01:21:20,427 --> 01:21:23,624
You give me a tie.
I give you a book.

1113
01:21:23,692 --> 01:21:27,140
Aunt Martha wants
an orange squeezer.

1114
01:21:27,211 --> 01:21:29,448
Uncle Harry can use a new pipe.

1115
01:21:32,740 --> 01:21:35,971
We forget nobody, adult or child.

1116
01:21:36,043 --> 01:21:38,200
All the stockings are filled.

1117
01:21:37,644 --> 01:21:39,499
All except one.

1118
01:22:03,916 --> 01:22:08,007
- I'm sorry, Matilda.
- Mr. Dudley, I knew you'd come back.

1119
01:22:08,075 --> 01:22:10,792
I knew you hadn't walked out on us.

1120
01:22:10,859 --> 01:22:12,136
Of course not.

1121
01:22:12,204 --> 01:22:15,019
Debby's been so worried
and Mrs. Brougham...

1122
01:22:15,084 --> 01:22:17,801
Run upstairs.
Tell Debby I'll see her later.

1123
01:22:17,868 --> 01:22:20,323
- I have some work to do.
- I'll tell her.

1124
01:23:05,227 --> 01:23:07,333
One moment, please.

1125
01:23:07,403 --> 01:23:10,022
- Is Mrs. Hamilton expecting you?
- No, but she'll want to see me.

1126
01:23:10,092 --> 01:23:14,282
- I'm the bishop's assistant.
- You're not expected, but the bishop is.

1127
01:23:14,348 --> 01:23:17,250
I told you, Stevens,
she'll wish to see me.

1128
01:24:44,267 --> 01:24:47,912
"This was composed for you,
my darling, and you only. Allan."

1129
01:24:47,980 --> 01:24:50,052
Her husbanïs name was George.

1130
01:26:49,292 --> 01:26:51,146
Good evening.

1131
01:26:52,651 --> 01:26:54,953
That music you were playing.

1132
01:26:55,019 --> 01:26:57,353
I'm the only one living
that knows that composition.

1133
01:26:58,155 --> 01:27:00,010
It's a shame that
we're the only ones...

1134
01:27:00,075 --> 01:27:02,279
who appreciate the lost genius of
Allan Cartwright.

1135
01:27:02,347 --> 01:27:05,129
- You know about him?
- Oh, yes.

1136
01:27:05,195 --> 01:27:09,058
The world lost a brilliant,
young composer when he died.

1137
01:27:10,091 --> 01:27:14,401
That was forty years ago.
You couldn't have known him.

1138
01:27:16,450 --> 01:27:19,338
I'm older than you think.
Come, let us sit down.

1139
01:27:25,068 --> 01:27:28,380
- What is your name?
- My name is Dudley.

1140
01:27:30,732 --> 01:27:33,640
Tell me about Allan and you.

1141
01:27:40,107 --> 01:27:41,384
Tell me.

1142
01:27:44,491 --> 01:27:48,070
Allan Cartwright
was the only man I ever loved.

1143
01:27:49,324 --> 01:27:51,178
We were engaged to be married.

1144
01:27:52,011 --> 01:27:53,866
I got frightened.

1145
01:27:54,667 --> 01:27:57,896
He had nothing and
I was afraid of poverty.

1146
01:27:57,964 --> 01:27:59,819
He went away.

1147
01:28:01,323 --> 01:28:03,178
I never saw him again.

1148
01:28:04,875 --> 01:28:07,242
I never loved George Hamilton.

1149
01:28:07,308 --> 01:28:09,675
He was very much in love with me.

1150
01:28:09,739 --> 01:28:12,440
He was wealthy.

1151
01:28:13,355 --> 01:28:16,651
I've spent a fortune honoring
his memory in empty monuments.

1152
01:28:27,755 --> 01:28:30,210
The Hamilton mansion.
Never been here before.

1153
01:28:30,283 --> 01:28:33,131
- What do I owe you?
- No charge. I'm not busy.

1154
01:28:33,195 --> 01:28:35,650
- Thank you, Sylvester.
- I'll be seeing you, Julia.

1155
01:28:43,915 --> 01:28:47,160
That must be Henry and Julia
at the door.

1156
01:28:46,635 --> 01:28:50,115
The bishop! I can't see him now.

1157
01:28:50,188 --> 01:28:52,710
- Oh, yes, you will.
- No!

1158
01:28:53,370 --> 01:28:53,961
Yes.

1159
01:28:55,916 --> 01:28:59,712
Just go out and greet them
in you usual warmhearted manner.

1160
01:29:04,300 --> 01:29:06,860
The Bishop and Mrs. Brougham
are calling, madame.

1161
01:29:13,067 --> 01:29:16,613
- You'll stay for dinner?
- I'm afraid I can't.

1162
01:29:16,684 --> 01:29:18,890
I have work to do.

1163
01:29:18,604 --> 01:29:20,630
Don't keep Henry and Julia waiting.

1164
01:29:32,811 --> 01:29:34,666
How do you do, Mrs. Hamilton?

1165
01:29:35,691 --> 01:29:38,179
How nice of you to come and see me.

1166
01:29:40,107 --> 01:29:41,995
Merry Christmas.

1167
01:29:43,404 --> 01:29:45,705
Let's go into the drawing room.

1168
01:29:51,755 --> 01:29:56,326
- Merry Christmas to you too.
- Oh, we're old friends. Call me Agnes.

1169
01:29:57,899 --> 01:29:59,754
You too, Julia, dear.

1170
01:29:59,819 --> 01:30:01,761
Yes, of course.

1171
01:30:06,379 --> 01:30:08,234
But he's gone already.

1172
01:30:08,715 --> 01:30:10,024
Who?

1173
01:30:12,235 --> 01:30:14,242
- He was here.
- I should have known it.

1174
01:30:14,315 --> 01:30:18,025
- Where did he go?
- The poor man had so much work to do.

1175
01:30:18,091 --> 01:30:19,946
You must make him take some rest.

1176
01:30:20,011 --> 01:30:21,866
I've been trying to.

1177
01:30:21,931 --> 01:30:25,706
I can't thank you enough
for sending him to me. But sit down.

1178
01:30:25,771 --> 01:30:31,008
Meeting Dudley has been the greatest
spiritual experience of my life.

1179
01:30:31,083 --> 01:30:32,293
I'm so glad.

1180
01:30:32,363 --> 01:30:34,949
How did you find him?

1181
01:30:35,019 --> 01:30:37,124
- It was an accident.
- It was a miracle.

1182
01:30:37,195 --> 01:30:41,188
Indeed. Talking with this
wonderful, understanding man has...

1183
01:30:42,891 --> 01:30:45,793
I've changed my mind
about the cathedral.

1184
01:30:45,867 --> 01:30:49,828
My money's going to those who need it.
The poor and the homeless.

1185
01:30:49,899 --> 01:30:53,958
The unappreciated people here
and around the world.

1186
01:30:54,027 --> 01:30:57,126
I want you to direct
the spending of the money.

1187
01:30:57,195 --> 01:30:59,813
- You see what Dudley has done?
- I see.

1188
01:30:59,883 --> 01:31:02,469
- Now you understand...
- Thank you, Mrs. Hamilton.

1189
01:31:04,171 --> 01:31:06,211
I'll be home later
for dinner, or something.

1190
01:31:06,987 --> 01:31:09,223
I don't know what...

1191
01:31:09,291 --> 01:31:11,146
Good-bye.

1192
01:31:55,692 --> 01:31:56,739
Hello, Professor.

1193
01:31:58,667 --> 01:32:00,720
Come in, my dear fellow.

1194
01:32:01,970 --> 01:32:03,620
Sit down.
Let me take your coat.

1195
01:32:03,691 --> 01:32:06,178
- No, thanks.
- Not there. Here.

1196
01:32:06,252 --> 01:32:08,324
This is the only reliable chair.

1197
01:32:08,395 --> 01:32:11,973
This is a surprise and an honor.

1198
01:32:12,043 --> 01:32:13,898
We must have a glass of sherry.

1199
01:32:13,963 --> 01:32:16,167
- No, thank you.
- I insist.

1200
01:32:16,235 --> 01:32:18,788
I want to show you something.

1201
01:32:18,859 --> 01:32:21,925
You see this bottle
and note that it is full?

1202
01:32:21,995 --> 01:32:23,457
Watch.

1203
01:32:23,810 --> 01:32:28,649
This is inexplicable even to you with
your vast ecclesiastical knowledge.

1204
01:32:31,787 --> 01:32:34,121
Observe that it is still full.

1205
01:32:34,187 --> 01:32:37,860
How do you account for that?
And the sherry.

1206
01:32:37,611 --> 01:32:40,742
It stimulates, warms and inspires.

1207
01:32:40,812 --> 01:32:43,975
But no matter how much you drink,
it never inebriates.

1208
01:32:44,043 --> 01:32:46,694
I can account for it.
Dudley's been here.

1209
01:32:48,299 --> 01:32:49,608
And that's not all.

1210
01:32:49,675 --> 01:32:52,163
He told me some things about history
that opened my eyes.

1211
01:32:52,235 --> 01:32:56,293
Today I went to the university library
and read some ancient texts...

1212
01:32:56,363 --> 01:33:00,420
which have been undecipherable
to living scholars.

1213
01:32:59,659 --> 01:33:03,008
Suddenly, I could understand them.

1214
01:33:03,083 --> 01:33:07,460
And this is what I have done,
thanks to Dudley.

1215
01:33:06,667 --> 01:33:09,799
I'm actually writing my history.

1216
01:33:09,867 --> 01:33:13,893
Let's face it. Dudley is no
mortal man like the rest of us.

1217
01:33:14,955 --> 01:33:16,995
Is he?

1218
01:33:17,067 --> 01:33:19,718
- How did you know?
- I can't tell.

1219
01:33:19,787 --> 01:33:22,275
- What is he?
- He says he's an angel.

1220
01:33:22,347 --> 01:33:25,478
- An angel.
- Nothing stopped me that time.

1221
01:33:25,970 --> 01:33:28,362
- From heaven?
- That I'm not sure about.

1222
01:33:28,427 --> 01:33:29,801
An angel.

1223
01:33:30,763 --> 01:33:33,349
Too bad. He's such a nice fellow.

1224
01:33:34,379 --> 01:33:36,233
I should have known.

1225
01:33:36,299 --> 01:33:39,180
Nothing less could have put me to work.

1226
01:33:38,635 --> 01:33:40,490
I'm glad he's done somebody some good.

1227
01:33:41,050 --> 01:33:42,464
He's brought nothing but disaster
for me.

1228
01:33:42,890 --> 01:33:45,670
That's absurd. He and Julia
were here the other day.

1229
01:33:45,739 --> 01:33:50,049
She seemed happy, quite like
her old, delightful self.

1230
01:33:50,123 --> 01:33:53,287
She's a different person
when she's with him.

1231
01:33:53,355 --> 01:33:55,243
He's made her despise me.

1232
01:33:56,139 --> 01:33:58,856
Are you sure he has done that?

1233
01:33:58,923 --> 01:34:01,476
- You think it's my fault?
- I didn't say that.

1234
01:34:01,970 --> 01:34:04,614
This is a mystery
beyond my powers of comprehension.

1235
01:34:04,683 --> 01:34:07,072
I suppose I am to blame
for everything.

1236
01:34:07,147 --> 01:34:09,122
I asked for this in more ways than one.

1237
01:34:10,795 --> 01:34:15,814
Dudley's presence only confirmed that
I'd already lost Julia and Debby's love.

1238
01:34:18,219 --> 01:34:20,674
I must confess, my old friend.

1239
01:34:20,747 --> 01:34:23,082
You generously sent me a coin.

1240
01:34:23,147 --> 01:34:27,402
And I only saw its commercial value.
Now I don't know where it is.

1241
01:34:27,467 --> 01:34:29,769
I do. Here it is.

1242
01:34:33,067 --> 01:34:35,369
Where did you find it?
Don't tell me.

1243
01:34:35,435 --> 01:34:40,137
And what's more he told me what it is.
A muzeum piece. Worth a fortune.

1244
01:34:40,203 --> 01:34:43,815
You keep it. Give it to Julia
as my Christmas present.

1245
01:34:43,883 --> 01:34:46,152
It might bring luck to you both.

1246
01:34:46,218 --> 01:34:48,706
It seems strange, you a bishop...

1247
01:34:48,779 --> 01:34:51,146
and me, a broken-down, old scholar.

1248
01:34:51,211 --> 01:34:53,099
I feel terribly sorry for you.

1249
01:34:53,163 --> 01:34:55,432
I wish I could help.

1250
01:34:55,499 --> 01:34:58,314
- There's nothing to be done.
- There must be.

1251
01:34:58,379 --> 01:35:01,249
You and Julia have always
loved each other.

1252
01:35:01,323 --> 01:35:03,047
That's only partially true.

1253
01:35:03,115 --> 01:35:05,351
- I love Julia...
- Then fight for her.

1254
01:35:05,418 --> 01:35:06,847
How can I?

1255
01:35:06,923 --> 01:35:09,258
You have a tremendous advantage.

1256
01:35:09,323 --> 01:35:12,356
- Advantage over an angel?
- That's precisely it.

1257
01:35:12,427 --> 01:35:15,110
He's an angel.
Julia is a creature of earth.

1258
01:35:15,178 --> 01:35:18,343
She's a woman and you are a man.

1259
01:35:29,739 --> 01:35:33,055
Isn't it beautiful?
He did every bit of it himself.

1260
01:35:33,131 --> 01:35:37,768
So quick too.
I couldn't believe my eyes.

1261
01:35:37,835 --> 01:35:42,112
- What a blessing he's been.
- The tree's lovely.

1262
01:35:42,187 --> 01:35:46,800
I'm glad you like it. It's been years
since I've decorated a tree.

1263
01:35:46,603 --> 01:35:50,200
I usually get
the more disagreeable jobs.

1264
01:35:52,811 --> 01:35:54,218
Good night, Matilda.

1265
01:35:54,282 --> 01:35:56,901
- Sweet dreams.
- Thank you, Mr. Dudley.

1266
01:36:07,755 --> 01:36:10,057
I think my work here is almost finished.

1267
01:36:10,123 --> 01:36:12,261
I'll have to be going.

1268
01:36:15,435 --> 01:36:17,639
Where will you be going?

1269
01:36:17,707 --> 01:36:19,976
Wherever they send me.

1270
01:36:20,043 --> 01:36:21,352
Who are they?

1271
01:36:22,635 --> 01:36:24,773
My superior officers.

1272
01:36:25,803 --> 01:36:29,152
Will we ever see you again?

1273
01:36:30,283 --> 01:36:32,650
They seldom send us
to the same place twice.

1274
01:36:32,715 --> 01:36:35,200
We might form attachments.

1275
01:36:36,139 --> 01:36:39,816
- I don't understand.
- Of course not.

1276
01:36:44,715 --> 01:36:46,602
- I don't want to leave.
- Why?

1277
01:36:48,203 --> 01:36:51,269
There are few people who know the
secret of making a heaven here on Earth.

1278
01:36:51,339 --> 01:36:53,095
You are one of them.

1279
01:36:57,131 --> 01:37:02,220
- I think you should go.
- Please don't send me away.

1280
01:37:03,851 --> 01:37:07,910
- What are you saying?
- I'm tired of wandering.

1281
01:37:07,979 --> 01:37:12,681
I'm tired of existing where one is
neither hot nor cold, hungry nor full.

1282
01:37:19,210 --> 01:37:21,669
You must go away and never come back.

1283
01:37:42,891 --> 01:37:47,331
I've never fought an angel, but take off
your coat and put up your dukes.

1284
01:37:47,403 --> 01:37:49,443
Why do you want to fight me?

1285
01:37:51,810 --> 01:37:56,103
Because you tried to steal my wife,
my child, the love that belongs to me.

1286
01:37:56,171 --> 01:37:58,025
Don't you realize that as an angel...

1287
01:37:58,091 --> 01:38:00,960
I could destroy you
with a bolt of lightning?

1288
01:38:01,035 --> 01:38:04,380
I don't care. Julia means
more to me than my life.

1289
01:38:03,659 --> 01:38:05,640
I'm not gonna lose her.

1290
01:38:08,363 --> 01:38:10,981
Then I have news for you.
I'm going.

1291
01:38:14,411 --> 01:38:16,996
I'll accept that when I see it.

1292
01:38:17,066 --> 01:38:18,408
No, you won't.

1293
01:38:18,475 --> 01:38:23,177
Because when I go you'll never know
an angel visited your house.

1294
01:38:23,242 --> 01:38:26,985
- What about Julia?
- She won't remember either.

1295
01:38:27,051 --> 01:38:30,280
Nor will Debby, the professor
or anyone else.

1296
01:38:31,947 --> 01:38:33,600
- I don't trust you.
- You may.

1297
01:38:35,210 --> 01:38:37,288
Because your prayer has been answered.

1298
01:38:37,355 --> 01:38:40,802
That's not true.
I was praying for a cathedral.

1299
01:38:40,874 --> 01:38:43,908
No, you were praying for guidance.

1300
01:38:43,979 --> 01:38:45,834
That has been given to you.

1301
01:38:52,683 --> 01:38:54,880
Just a minute, please.

1302
01:38:55,659 --> 01:38:57,640
Good-bye, Henry.

1303
01:39:04,010 --> 01:39:07,207
If we need you again,
will you come back?

1304
01:39:07,275 --> 01:39:09,010
Not I.

1305
01:39:08,619 --> 01:39:12,131
I should ask to be assigned
to the other end of the universe.

1306
01:39:12,202 --> 01:39:15,104
Because I was so difficult?

1307
01:39:15,178 --> 01:39:17,033
This difficulty was in me.

1308
01:39:17,098 --> 01:39:21,987
When an immortal envies the mortal
entrusted to him it's a danger signal.

1309
01:39:23,083 --> 01:39:25,417
Take her in your arms
and hold her tight.

1310
01:39:26,442 --> 01:39:28,297
Coming.

1311
01:39:29,259 --> 01:39:31,266
Kiss her for me, you lucky Henry.

1312
01:40:21,040 --> 01:40:22,409
She's asleep.

1313
01:40:24,970 --> 01:40:26,825
Are you all right?

1314
01:40:27,723 --> 01:40:30,280
Of course I am.

1315
01:40:30,922 --> 01:40:32,832
Did you get that for Debby?

1316
01:40:38,762 --> 01:40:40,617
I can't imagine where it came from.

1317
01:40:52,171 --> 01:40:54,243
Why, Henry. What is it?

1318
01:40:55,810 --> 01:40:57,440
I don't know. L...

1319
01:40:57,650 --> 01:41:00,776
I just have the most inexplicable
feeling of happiness.

1320
01:41:01,994 --> 01:41:03,423
- You know something?
- What?

1321
01:41:03,498 --> 01:41:05,407
There's a big bowl of cider downstairs.

1322
01:41:05,482 --> 01:41:07,043
That's for tomorrow afternoon.

1323
01:41:07,115 --> 01:41:09,860
Let's drink it now. To us.

1324
01:41:09,611 --> 01:41:11,466
To our happiness and what lies ahead.

1325
01:41:11,810 --> 01:41:14,281
Then let's smash the glasses
in the fireplace.

1326
01:41:15,434 --> 01:41:16,808
Listen.

1327
01:41:19,339 --> 01:41:21,600
That's coming from St. Timothy's.

1328
01:41:22,795 --> 01:41:26,341
Let's have the cider
after your Christmas Eve sermon.

1329
01:41:26,411 --> 01:41:28,990
- Oh, my sermon.
- Yes.

1330
01:41:28,618 --> 01:41:30,112
That's better still.

1331
01:41:32,075 --> 01:41:36,646
Ring the bells in adoration

1332
01:41:41,675 --> 01:41:44,991
We pour
We pour to Thee

1333
01:41:45,067 --> 01:41:49,300
Our supplication

1334
01:41:48,651 --> 01:41:50,854
That Thou wouldst

1335
01:41:50,923 --> 01:41:53,705
Grant us Lord

1336
01:41:53,771 --> 01:41:59,434
Salvation

1337
01:42:13,003 --> 01:42:15,392
Tonight I want to tell you the story...

1338
01:42:15,466 --> 01:42:17,321
of an empty stocking.

1339
01:42:20,235 --> 01:42:22,602
Once upon a midnight clear...

1340
01:42:22,667 --> 01:42:24,720
there was a chilïs cry.

1341
01:42:26,880 --> 01:42:28,775
A blazing star hung over a stable...

1342
01:42:30,282 --> 01:42:32,421
and wise men came with birthday gifts.

1343
01:42:34,314 --> 01:42:37,314
We haven't forgotten that night
down the centuries.

1344
01:42:37,386 --> 01:42:40,256
We celebrate it with stars
on Christmas trees...

1345
01:42:40,330 --> 01:42:43,233
with the sound of bells
and with gifts.

1346
01:42:43,979 --> 01:42:46,117
Especially with gifts.

1347
01:42:46,954 --> 01:42:48,809
You give me a book.

1348
01:42:48,875 --> 01:42:51,046
I give you a tie.

1349
01:42:51,115 --> 01:42:55,130
Aunt Martha wants an orange squeezer.

1350
01:42:54,635 --> 01:42:58,050
Uncle Henry can use a new pipe.

1351
01:42:59,083 --> 01:43:02,148
We forget nobody, adult or child.

1352
01:43:02,219 --> 01:43:04,706
All the stockings are filled.

1353
01:43:04,778 --> 01:43:08,040
All, that is, except one.

1354
01:43:09,130 --> 01:43:12,676
And we have even forgotten
to hang it up.

1355
01:43:12,746 --> 01:43:16,194
A stocking for the child
born in a manger.

1356
01:43:16,267 --> 01:43:18,274
It's His birthday we're celebrating.

1357
01:43:19,307 --> 01:43:22,154
Let's not ever forget that.

1358
01:43:22,218 --> 01:43:24,455
Let us ask ourselves...

1359
01:43:24,720 --> 01:43:27,304
what He would wish for most.

1360
01:43:27,370 --> 01:43:30,305
And then let each put in his share.

1361
01:43:31,818 --> 01:43:36,128
Loving kindness, warm hearts...

1362
01:43:36,202 --> 01:43:39,780
and the stretched-out hand of tolerance.

1363
01:43:39,850 --> 01:43:43,014
All the shining gifts


